item.title: Compiling error**16 errors**
item.dc:creator: @Budda Budda
item.description:
@Budda wrote:

lawlzorz doesnt knsow methods!
lawlzorz doesnt knsow methods!"
lawlzorz doesnt knsow methods!"
lawlzorz doesnt knsow methods!"

LOOK AT THE FUCKING ERRORS:

NPCHandler.java:1597: cannot find symbol symbol : method randomtrain() location: class Item ItemHandler.addItem(Item.randomtrain(), npcs[NPCID].absX, npcs[NPCID].absY, 1, G etNpcKiller(NPCID), false);
First line: NPCHandler.java:1597: cannot find symbol
Means in NPCHandler.java on line 1597, it cannot find a symbol.
What is the symbol? Look at the next line: symbol : method randomtrain()
So the symbol is a method called “randomtrain()”. So it cannot find the method “randomtrain()”.
Look at the forth line, it even shows you where you were trying to use it: ItemHandler.addItem(Item.randomtrain(), npcs[NPCID].absX, npcs[NPCID].absY, 1, G etNpcKiller(NPCID), false);
So, taking from the first line, you are in NPCHandler, trying to call the addItem method in ItemHandler. Look at the first variable in that method: Item.randomtrain()
There we go! So the method you are missing, “randomtrain()” in the Item class.

Looking further into it, you can go to ItemHandler, and find the addItem method, and it would show you something along the lines of: addItem(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, boolean f)
Looking at the first variable again, a, it is an integer. Since “randomtrain()” is meant to give you that variable, it must be an int.
So, in Item.java, add a method starting like:

public int randomtrain() { return -1; }

Of course you will need to add in the other needed things to return the right integer, but what I have given you will compile.

Savvy?
